Explanation:

- I inspected app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/UserController.php and found the index() method returns a ResourceCollection of App\Http\Resources\User via UserResource::collection(...->paginate(...)).
- I opened App\Http/Resources/User.php and App\Http/Resources/Role.php to determine the exact fields serialized for each user and role.
- The User resource serializes these fields: id, name, email, provider, provider_id, registered_at (ISO 8601 string), comments_count, posts_count, roles (array of Role resources). Role resource serializes: id, name.
- The controller uses paginate(), and Laravel resource collections include the standard top-level pagination structure: data (array of items), links (first, last, prev, next) and meta (current_page, from, last_page, links[], path, per_page, to, total). I included those standard pagination properties in the response schema.
- I produced a Swagger 2.0-style Responses object for the GET /v1/users endpoint containing a single 200 response with a JSON schema describing the paginated response and the user and role objects. I did not use $ref and I only included fields present in the resources and the standard pagination envelope.

